What Capitalism Was - Etoile Polaire - Plays the Music of Phillip Glass on Accordion What Capitalism Was - Subterraneans - Plays the Music of Phillip Glass on Accordion Chumbawamba - Dumbing Down (looping) - WYSIWYG What Capitalism Was - Resource - Plays the Music of Phillip Glass on Accordion What Capitalism Was - Knee 1 - Plays the Music of Phillip Glass on Accordion - Test Department - Comrade Enver Hoxva - Tactics for Evolution King Crimson - Epitaph - In the Court of the Crimson Kng The Kleptones - Mad Groove - Uptime Shooby Taylor, the Human Horn - Somewhere Over the Rainbow - Shooby Sings, 111838=Latest newsletter: May 2015, 30574=interview with guest Wendy Westerwelle regarding Soph: An Evening with the Last of the Red-Hot Mamas playing till Dec 26 2010 at the Coho Theatre ..., 102000=Here we are, with another episode of Radio Lost and Found - and the last one of 2010. At about the halfway mark, I mixed a mediascape of Senator Bernie Sanders heroic, though sadly ignored voice of reason filibuster speech to the Senate - trying to dissuade his colleagues to stop counting their cash long enough to vote no on the Bush/Obama tax cuts for billionaires. It's like hearing an obituary for the American dream - at least the one we're all supposed to live in - as opposed to the one that the wealthiest 2% get to live in. Sad, but worth listening to (Sanders' speech, not necessarily my mediascape)., 18963=Suprise, Suprise!!  I do get to do a December show after all!  I filled in for Sun Lee, who was at Roger Waters' show.  We opened with a couple of cuts from the new Garcia Estate Rhino release "Ragged But Right", the follow up (but never released)  c.d. of Jerry Garcia Acoustic Band "Almost Acoustic" c.d. It's now available for purchace at WWW.DEAD.NET  Next came the original version of "The Other Side Of This Life", a 1965 recording by Fred Neil. Then, things began to get wet. Several callers said that it was kind of strange looking out of the window and seeing heavy rain falling, and hearing it coming out of the speakers at the same time! I love our listening Audience! The Main Ten was the culpret. It was just a little peek of what was coming later in the show. "Main Ten" was from Mickey Hart "Rolling Thunder".  We polished off our "Rain Set" with a cut from the Garcia Band cd Cat's Down Under The Stars. Donna Jean did the vocal honors on "Rain".  For the next hour and a half or so, we played the second set of H. J. Kaiser, Oakland 11-7-87 Set 2 as promised on last month's show. We had just enough time to play one more cut from "Ragged But Right" to close it out and hand it off to Tom Wendt "Blues Junction".  Happy Holidays to you all!!! See you next year!, 120261=Copyright © 2012 KBOO Community Radio | Copyright Policy | Community Guidelines | Website Illustration & Design by: KMF ILLUSTRATION}
